== Maus: A Survivor's Tale: My Father Bleeds History
==== Author: Art Spiegelman
==== Read on: Jan 2022
It's a 2 part book recommended by my friend.

This book describes about the struggles faced by a merchant in World War II. It chose a comic style and has some fun parts as the conversation is between a son and his father where the father is an old person and has his own idiosyncratic actions which irritates son. Few parts of the conversation makes us to think because we all always have these sort of conversations with our grandparents who talk a bit old-fashioned and are insane (atleast from our point of view) because the hardships they had seen are way more different from the hardships we face now.

Atleast, I personally feel that our parents and grandparents faced more difficulties than us. That doesn't mean that we don't have any difficulties. Ours are not existential crisis while most of our parents/grandparents had existential crisis which is definitely more tough to live compared to our day.

Also, the author conveys the series of incidents occurred in WW II including Auschwitz holocaust which might be one of the world's horrible experience. But his writing style is bit relaxing and we might not feel that much trauma when reading it.

Books on a similar line are: "The Diary of a Young Girl", "Man's search for Meaning"

